      "scenario": "You are the CFO of GlobalTrade Inc., a Canadian import-export company. During a quarterly review, you notice unusual patterns in transactions with a new overseas distributor, MegaCorp Ltd., based in a jurisdiction known for weak anti-money laundering controls.\n\nKey observations:\n- Purchase invoices from MegaCorp for industrial equipment show prices 40% above market rates\n- Shipping documents indicate weights inconsistent with the invoiced goods\n- Three transactions totaling $2.8M were paid to MegaCorp, but only $1.9M in goods were received and recorded in inventory\n- MegaCorp requested payments be split between bank accounts in three different countries\n- The sales manager who initiated the relationship with MegaCorp recently purchased a luxury vehicle\n- MegaCorp is owned by a shell company with nominee directors\n\nYour preliminary investigation reveals that similar goods could be purchased from reputable suppliers at significantly lower prices. The sales manager claims MegaCorp offers 'unique quality' and 'strategic partnership opportunities.'",
